---
import Default from '../../layouts/Default.astro';
import Hero from '../../components/Hero.astro';
import SectionHead from '../../components/SectionHead.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
---
<Default title="Autonomous Research Lab · Harshith Kantamneni" description="A multi-agent research lab studying why autonomous engineering systems quietly fail their own tests." current="labs">

  <Hero
    meta={['Active 2026', '~31 to 73 agents']}
  >
    Autonomous<br />Research Lab.
  </Hero>

  <div class="page-grid">
    <p class="extended measure-narrow lede" style="margin-top: var(--space-6);">
      Why do autonomous labs pass their own tests while the work quietly breaks? This
      lab runs experiments to find out, and writes up what holds.
    </p>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="THESIS" title="The thesis" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight drop-cap">
      <p>Most multi-agent labs collapse because they grade themselves. Self-grading creates a flat verification surface, which is the system's view of its own correctness. Any sufficiently capable optimizer climbs that surface without solving the underlying problem. The lab passes its own tests. The work quietly breaks.</p>
      <p>This lab investigates three candidate fixes: external verdicts, pre-registered falsifiers, and adversarial payoffs. Each one gets tested across cycles. Cycles where the fix holds get compared to cycles where it doesn't.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <PullQuote attribution="Lab principle">
    A verification surface is only as deep as the things it cannot see.
  </PullQuote>

  <SectionHead marker="METHOD" title="The method" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>Four Claude opus instances review each other, plus a cross-family judge for control. Same-family judge bias is real, so the cross-family layer is what keeps the experiment honest. Without it, you're just adding chairs to the same review board.</p>
      <p>Each cycle produces an artifact: ratified principles, archived rejections, and the reasoning for both. Methodology is the output. The engineering is just the medium.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="OUTPUT" title="What gets published" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>Long-form reports go up about once a month. They're the public surface. Cycle transcripts and specialist working memory stay private.</p>
      <p>Notes are shorter and come out more often. One cycle, one finding, one directive that came out of it. Sometimes inconclusive on purpose.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

</Default>
